    <fr:title text="Extended Natural Numbers">Extended Natural Numbers</fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>The extended natural numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}_\infty ]]></fr:tex> are the final coalgebra for the functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \mapsto  X \uplus  1]]></fr:tex> in the category of sets. Concretely these can be constructed as monotone functions from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> to the booleans. Since the natural numbers are the initial algebra for the same functor we get an canonical injective function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N} \to  \mathbb {N}_\infty ]]></fr:tex>. We say an extended natural number is <html:em>finite</html:em> if it is in the image of this function.</html:p>
    <html:p>In classical mathematics, the extended natural numbers are simply a coproduct of the natural numbers with a single "infinite" point. Constructively, we can define a function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N} \uplus  1 \to  \mathbb {N} \to  \mathbb {N}_\infty ]]></fr:tex> and it being an isomorphism is one of the formulations of <fr:link href="/QCIE/" title="Markov's Principle" uri="https://um-catlab.github.io/QCIE/" display-uri="QCIE" type="local">Markov's principle</fr:link>.</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
